<br>
Rune 4 - Level 44<br>
Cost of Component:  10,pp 5 gp<br>
Type:  Single Target Damage Absorption <br>
Max Duration:  1 hour 30 minutes <br>
Casting Time:  5 seconds <br>
Recast Time:  Instant <br>
Actual Effects: Target: Absorb Damage (305 - 394) <br>
<br>
Rune 5- level 52<br>
Cost of Component:  10pp 5gp <br>
Type:  Single Target Damage Absorption <br>
Max Duration:  1 hour 50 minutes <br>
Casting Time:  5 seconds <br>
Recast Time:  Instant <br>
Actual Effects: Target: Absorb Damage (620 - 700) <br>
<br>
<br>
The basic problem is one of cost vs efficiancy.  Rune 3 has a 230 point barrier, and only cost you 7gp ( or, less than one PP ) to cast it.  You can easily use this spell and break even on the cost, just by looting normal PP from mobs.<br>
<br>
Rune 4 cost over 10 TIMES the price to cast ( since you need to purchase a peridot that cost 10pp 5 gp ), and at its BEST protection is not quite 2 times the protection of rune 3.<br>
<br>
To put it another way, you can cast rune 3 10 times, and still have spent less money than it cost you to cast rune 4 once.  Casting 10 rune 3s MUCH better than casting 1 rune 4, from a cost stand point. <br>
<br>
When you get rune 5, the creatures are hitting for more than 130 a pop, so if you NEED a rune, you generally want the best one, and cost isnt so much of an issue. When you get rune 3, it generally stops a couple rounds of combat for you.  Rune 5 does the same thing for a higher level enchanter, and at this point the cost is not important.<br>
<br>
Rune 4 comes at a time when the cost is still important, and doesnt provide enough benifit for the cost.  The spell should actually take a 5pp component like a pearl or something, then it would get used.<br>
<br>
Sorry for the long winded explanation again.. its my nature i guess heh.<br>
